<h2><br/>
Universal bounds and thermodynamic tradeoffs in nonequilibrium energy harvesting</h2>
<p>Jordi Piñero, Ricard Solé, Artemy Kolchinsky</p>
<p>Many molecular systems operate by harvesting and storing energy from their environments. However, the maintenance of a nonequilibrium state necessary to support energy harvesting itself carries thermodynamic costs. We consider the optimal tradeoff between costs and benefits of energy harvesting in a nonequilibrium steady state, for a system that may be in contact with a fluctuating environment. We find a universal bound on this tradeoff, which leads to closed-form expressions for optimal power output and optimal steady-state distributions for three physically meaningful regimes. Our results are illustrated using a model of a unicyclic network, which is inspired by the logic of biomolecular cycles.</p>
<p>Read the full article at: <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.04975v1" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">arxiv.org</a></p>
